WEBVTT

1
00:00:37,084 --> 00:00:38,290
(BEEPING)

2
00:00:56,737 --> 00:00:57,977
Come on!

3
00:01:14,188 --> 00:01:15,667
(SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

4
00:01:40,781 --> 00:01:41,987
(BEEPING CONTINUES)

5
00:01:55,629 --> 00:01:57,131
(CAR ALARM SOUNDING)

6
00:02:05,940 --> 00:02:08,181
(POLICE RADIO CHATTER)

7
00:02:21,388 --> 00:02:24,130
But you realize 
I know nothing about politics?

8
00:02:24,258 --> 00:02:26,670
-You voted for him, didn't you? 
-Adam Lang? Of course I did.

9
00:02:26,727 --> 00:02:30,038
Everyone voted for him. 
He wasn't a politician, he was a craze.

10
00:02:30,097 --> 00:02:31,440
Well, there you go.

11
00:02:31,498 --> 00:02:36,072
Look, it's a new ghostwriter he needs, 
not another goddamn politico.

12
00:02:36,437 --> 00:02:39,281
He was paid $10 million for these memoirs,

13
00:02:39,340 --> 00:02:42,321
but rumor has it 
the manuscript's a crock of shit.

14
00:02:42,376 --> 00:02:45,550
Rhinehart's lending him his house 
at the ocean so they can fix it,

15
00:02:45,713 --> 00:02:48,353
and the pressure 
must have gotten to McAra.

16
00:02:48,682 --> 00:02:51,094
Pathologist said his blood was, 
like, three parts booze.

17
00:02:51,151 --> 00:02:53,222
You mean he drowned by accident?

18
00:02:53,454 --> 00:02:56,867
Accident, suicide, who cares? 
It was the book that killed him.

19
00:02:57,091 --> 00:02:58,195
Well, that's encouraging.

20
00:02:58,258 --> 00:02:59,259
(CHUCKLES DRYLY)

21
00:02:59,426 --> 00:03:01,133
Who is this McAra? 
Should I have heard of him?

22
00:03:01,195 --> 00:03:05,200
Yeah. He was some kind of aide to Lang 
when he was Prime Minister,

23
00:03:05,265 --> 00:03:08,144
so don't admit that you haven't. 
He was with him for years.

24
00:03:08,202 --> 00:03:09,272
(SIGHING)

25
00:03:11,138 --> 00:03:12,879
I don't know, Rick.

26
00:03:15,776 --> 00:03:18,450
This is a great opportunity for you.

27
00:03:18,612 --> 00:03:20,592
Plus the money is good. Kids won't starve.

28
00:03:20,647 --> 00:03:22,558
-l don't have any kids. 
-l do.

29
00:03:37,131 --> 00:03:38,235
Roy.

30
00:03:40,634 --> 00:03:41,704
(BEEPING)

31
00:03:42,336 --> 00:03:44,111
Who're you expecting to bomb you, 
Random House?

32
00:03:44,171 --> 00:03:45,582
We're publishing Lang's memoirs.

33
00:03:45,639 --> 00:03:48,279
That's enough to make us a target, 
apparently.

34
00:03:48,876 --> 00:03:50,253
Thank you.

35
00:03:59,520 --> 00:04:03,366
-How many have you seen? 
-Five. You're the last.

36
00:04:07,027 --> 00:04:08,734
(CARD READER BEEPS)

37
00:04:10,964 --> 00:04:12,204
I must be honest.

38
00:04:12,266 --> 00:04:14,439
I don't think you're the right man 
for this assignment.

39
00:04:14,501 --> 00:04:16,276
Then it's a good job 
it's not your decision, Roy.

40
00:04:18,872 --> 00:04:21,978
John Maddox, chief executive 
of Rhinehart, New York.

41
00:04:22,042 --> 00:04:23,043
Sir.

42
00:04:24,344 --> 00:04:26,847
Sidney Kroll, 
Mr. Lang's Washington attorney.

43
00:04:26,914 --> 00:04:27,915
Mr. Kroll.

44
00:04:27,981 --> 00:04:30,985
And Nick Ricardelli I believe you know.

45
00:04:31,351 --> 00:04:32,352
All right, Rick.

46
00:04:36,323 --> 00:04:39,566
JOHN: All right, I gather from Rick 
you're aware of the situation?

47
00:04:40,994 --> 00:04:42,405
Perhaps you can enlighten us

48
00:04:42,463 --> 00:04:45,603
and tell us what exactly 
you're gonna bring to this project.

49
00:04:45,699 --> 00:04:46,939
Nothing.

50
00:04:47,568 --> 00:04:48,638
(LAUGHING)

51
00:04:49,369 --> 00:04:51,576
No, I'm not gonna pretend 
to be someone I'm not.

52
00:04:51,638 --> 00:04:53,140
You have my CV.

53
00:04:53,207 --> 00:04:56,518
His last effort was 
the autobiography of a magician,

54
00:04:56,577 --> 00:04:58,853
I Came, I Sawed, I Conquered.

55
00:04:58,912 --> 00:05:01,654
Yeah, and it went straight 
to number one, so...

56
00:05:01,715 --> 00:05:03,888
After you turned it down, Roy.

57
00:05:04,418 --> 00:05:08,525
Look, I don't read political memoirs. 
Who does?

58
00:05:09,756 --> 00:05:13,363
And I gather you've spent 
$10 million on this book.

59
00:05:13,760 --> 00:05:16,001
How much of that are you gonna see back?

60
00:05:16,063 --> 00:05:18,202
Two? Three?

61
00:05:18,265 --> 00:05:20,541
It's bad news for your shareholders.

62
00:05:20,601 --> 00:05:23,605
And it's worse news 
for your client, Mr. Kroll.

63
00:05:23,670 --> 00:05:28,380
Adam Lang, he wants a place in history, 
not in the remainder tables.

64
00:05:28,442 --> 00:05:29,546
Oh, please!

65
00:05:29,610 --> 00:05:31,817
It's because I know nothing about politics

66
00:05:31,879 --> 00:05:35,588
that I'll ask the questions that get 
right to the heart of who Adam Lang is.

67
00:05:35,749 --> 00:05:38,127
And that is what sells autobiographies.

68
00:05:38,719 --> 00:05:39,925
Heart.

69
00:05:41,822 --> 00:05:44,268
Wow! That's nicely done.

70
00:05:44,324 --> 00:05:46,964
-What utter balls. 
-You think so?

71
00:05:47,027 --> 00:05:50,736
John, of course. 
Adam Lang's a world historical figure.

72
00:05:50,797 --> 00:05:53,277
His autobiography is gonna be 
a world-publishing event.

73
00:05:53,333 --> 00:05:56,075
Yeah, well, I got warehouses filled with

74
00:05:56,136 --> 00:05:58,810
world-publishing events 
waiting to be pulped.

75
00:06:00,374 --> 00:06:01,478
Sid?

76
00:06:02,242 --> 00:06:06,156
Adam is obviously still very upset 
by what happened to Mike McAra.

77
00:06:06,213 --> 00:06:10,593
He was irreplaceable. 
Irreplaceable, and yet he has to be replaced.

78
00:06:11,652 --> 00:06:16,158
Adam can certainly appreciate the benefits 
of trying someone different.

79
00:06:16,223 --> 00:06:19,432
In the end, it's about chemistry. 
Do you work out, maybe?

80
00:06:19,493 --> 00:06:21,939
-Not really. 
-That's a pity. Adam likes to work out.

81
00:06:21,995 --> 00:06:25,499
Actually, I know a good writer 
on the Guardian who uses a gym.

82
00:06:25,566 --> 00:06:26,840
(RICK SCOFFS)

83
00:06:27,267 --> 00:06:31,841
Okay, maybe we could just run over 
the publishing schedule, yeah?

84
00:06:31,905 --> 00:06:33,350
We need to wrap this up in a month.

85
00:06:33,407 --> 00:06:34,647
-GHOST: A month? 
-Yes.

86
00:06:34,708 --> 00:06:36,881
-You want the book in a month? 
-We already have a first draft.

87
00:06:36,944 --> 00:06:39,584
Yeah, well, it needs a lot of work.

88
00:06:40,180 --> 00:06:44,526
That's why I like your résumé here. 
You're fast, and you deliver.

89
00:06:44,585 --> 00:06:47,395
You name it, he ghosts it. (CHUCKLES)

90
00:06:47,621 --> 00:06:48,998
And you're a Brit.

91
00:06:49,957 --> 00:06:51,163
The ghost should be a Brit.

92
00:06:51,225 --> 00:06:53,364
(IMITATES BRITISH ACCENT) 
To get the jolly old tone right, right?

93
00:06:53,427 --> 00:06:54,701
(CHUCKLING)

94
00:06:54,861 --> 00:06:58,832
-Do you have any family commitments? 
-No, I have no family. Why?

95
00:06:58,899 --> 00:07:00,640
Adam is locked into a US lecture tour,

96
00:07:00,701 --> 00:07:04,774
also a fundraising program 
for the Adam Lang Foundation.

97
00:07:04,838 --> 00:07:06,943
It's a month in the States. That's okay.

98
00:07:07,007 --> 00:07:08,987
Couldn't I bring the manuscript back here 
to work on?

99
00:07:09,042 --> 00:07:13,422
I'm afraid not. it's in a secure environment 
in Marty Rhinehart's own house.

100
00:07:13,680 --> 00:07:15,853
Only a few people are allowed to handle it.

101
00:07:15,916 --> 00:07:17,486
Sounds more like a bomb than a book.

102
00:07:17,551 --> 00:07:18,655
(CHUCKLES)

103
00:07:19,486 --> 00:07:23,764
I will need to see it myself at some point. 
I am supposed to be editing it.

104
00:07:23,824 --> 00:07:27,271
Yeah, in theory. 
Actually, we need to talk about that.

105
00:07:29,296 --> 00:07:31,139
-JOHN: How soon can you get over there? 
-As soon as you want.

106
00:07:31,198 --> 00:07:32,336
-He'll fly tonight. 
-Rick.

107
00:07:32,399 --> 00:07:33,400
(SOFTLY) it's okay.

108
00:07:41,375 --> 00:07:42,820
Okay, you're in.

109
00:07:44,211 --> 00:07:45,212
Oh!

110
00:07:45,312 --> 00:07:47,349
-(GRUNTS) Congratulations. 
-Thank you. Thanks.

111
00:07:47,414 --> 00:07:48,825
-Rick. 
-Thank you.

112
00:07:48,882 --> 00:07:51,556
Actually, I have something here

113
00:07:51,618 --> 00:07:52,824
-you might want to look at. 
-ls that... Is that...

114
00:07:52,886 --> 00:07:55,696
No, no, no, this isn't Adam's book. 
No, it's another client of mine.

115
00:07:55,756 --> 00:07:58,202
Yeah, perhaps you can let me know 
what you think.

116
00:07:59,559 --> 00:08:00,663
Sure.

117
00:08:00,727 --> 00:08:02,536
JOHN: Okay, if you're gonna get 
that evening flight,

118
00:08:02,596 --> 00:08:05,042
we'd better talk contracts with Rick here.

119
00:08:05,098 --> 00:08:07,908
Wanna show our friend to the door? 
Would you?

120
00:08:08,068 --> 00:08:09,172
Roy?

121
00:08:11,171 --> 00:08:13,117
RICK: Call you in an hour, buddy.

122
00:08:13,273 --> 00:08:14,274
JOHN: Hey!

123
00:08:14,741 --> 00:08:15,811
Remember...

124
00:08:17,944 --> 00:08:19,446
(IMITATES BRITISH ACCENT) Heart.

125
00:08:22,683 --> 00:08:26,256
There's something not quite right 
about this project.

126
00:08:26,420 --> 00:08:28,422
-What? Me, you mean? 
-Obviously you.

127
00:08:28,588 --> 00:08:30,932
And McAra. Suicide?

128
00:08:32,092 --> 00:08:35,039
He didn't strike me as the suicidal type.

129
00:08:35,195 --> 00:08:36,936
Always nice to see you, Roy.

130
00:08:39,700 --> 00:08:40,940
ROY: Good luck.

131
00:08:53,513 --> 00:08:55,823
Oh, God.

132
00:09:11,164 --> 00:09:12,666
TAXI DRIVER: Thank you.

133
00:09:19,139 --> 00:09:20,209
(GRUNTING)

134
00:09:48,435 --> 00:09:49,743
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

135
00:09:54,174 --> 00:09:56,211
-Yeah? 
-RICK: Congratulations!

136
00:09:56,276 --> 00:09:58,847
-On what? 
-On having me as your agent.

137
00:09:59,012 --> 00:10:01,014
Yeah, I can hardly believe my luck.

138
00:10:01,181 --> 00:10:02,182
Are you packed?

139
00:10:02,249 --> 00:10:03,694
I just got mugged.

140
00:10:04,885 --> 00:10:07,627
Shit! Are you okay?

141
00:10:07,687 --> 00:10:11,533
Yeah, all they took was the manuscript 
that Sidney Kroll gave me.

142
00:10:11,691 --> 00:10:13,227
What? Why?

143
00:10:13,560 --> 00:10:15,301
I don't know. You tell me.

144
00:10:16,163 --> 00:10:17,198
Are you hurt?

145
00:10:17,264 --> 00:10:20,370
No, I'm fine. I think they must 
have followed me from Rhinehart's.

146
00:10:21,468 --> 00:10:23,243
Why would they do that?

147
00:10:23,403 --> 00:10:26,316
Well, maybe they thought 
I had Lang's book.

148
00:10:26,473 --> 00:10:28,749
I knew this whole thing was a bad idea.

149
00:10:30,510 --> 00:10:32,012
You're still okay to fly tonight, right?

150
00:10:32,079 --> 00:10:34,184
For God's sake, Rick, I'm in shock.

151
00:10:34,247 --> 00:10:36,591
Well, here's another shock for you.

152
00:10:36,750 --> 00:10:39,560
For one month's work 
on a manuscript that's already written,

153
00:10:39,619 --> 00:10:45,570
Rhinehart Inc. is willing 
to pay you $250, 000, plus expenses.

154
00:10:46,893 --> 00:10:48,600
Window seat or aisle?

155
00:10:48,995 --> 00:10:52,238
FEMALE NEWSREADER: ...Islam has 
issued a statement claiming responsibility.

156
00:10:52,299 --> 00:10:55,246
We hope to bring you more on that 
later in the bulletin.

157
00:10:55,302 --> 00:10:59,341
Meanwhile, former British Prime Minister 
Adam Lang is back in the news tonight.

158
00:10:59,439 --> 00:11:02,283
According to leaked documents, 
Mr. Lang authorized

159
00:11:02,342 --> 00:11:04,515
the illegal use of British special forces

160
00:11:04,578 --> 00:11:08,617
to seize four suspected al-Qaeda terrorists 
in Pakistan

161
00:11:08,682 --> 00:11:12,459
and then hand them over 
for interrogation by the CIA.

162
00:11:12,619 --> 00:11:16,761
The men, Nasir Ashraf Marwat Sayed, 
Salim Khan and Faruk Ahmed,

163
00:11:16,823 --> 00:11:21,772
all British citizens, were seized in the 
Pakistani city of Peshawar five years ago.

164
00:11:22,162 --> 00:11:25,302
All four were allegedly transferred 
out of the country

165
00:11:25,365 --> 00:11:27,811
to a secret location and tortured.

166
00:11:27,868 --> 00:11:30,212
Mr. Ashraf is reported to have died 
under interrogation.

167
00:11:30,270 --> 00:11:31,305
(PHONE RINGING)

168
00:11:31,371 --> 00:11:33,373
Such an operation 
would have been illegal under...

169
00:11:33,440 --> 00:11:35,078
-RICK: Yeah? 
-Where are you?

170
00:11:35,141 --> 00:11:38,520
Heathrow, like you. 
Waiting for my flight to New York.

171
00:11:38,578 --> 00:11:39,579
Can you see the news?

172
00:11:39,646 --> 00:11:42,183
The Lang story? Yeah, I'm watching it now.

173
00:11:42,249 --> 00:11:44,525
What have you gotten me into?

174
00:11:44,584 --> 00:11:49,055
I got you into a quarter of a million bucks, 
pal, that's what I got you into.

175
00:11:49,289 --> 00:11:50,700
They're calling my flight. I gotta go.

176
00:11:50,757 --> 00:11:52,236
Listen, I just realized

177
00:11:52,292 --> 00:11:55,068
Sidney Kroll could have given me 
that manuscript deliberately

178
00:11:55,128 --> 00:11:58,007
so it would look like 
I was carrying Lang's book.

179
00:11:58,064 --> 00:11:59,338
Why the hell would he do that?

180
00:11:59,399 --> 00:12:03,142
I don't know. To use me as a tethered goat?

181
00:12:04,404 --> 00:12:07,146
Get some sleep on the plane. 
You're sounding weird.

182
00:12:07,207 --> 00:12:10,677
(SCOFFS) "A tethered goat." 
I'll call you next week.

183
00:12:10,744 --> 00:12:12,883
FEMALE NEWSREADER: 
...and long-term psychological trauma.

184
00:12:12,946 --> 00:12:14,425
In other words, torture.

185
00:12:14,948 --> 00:12:16,154
Hello, sir. 
Would you like a newspaper to read?

186
00:12:16,216 --> 00:12:18,492
-Have you got the Evening Standard? 
-We do, yes.

187
00:12:18,552 --> 00:12:20,190
Thanks. Thank you.

188
00:12:20,453 --> 00:12:22,194
STEWARDESS: Hello, madam. 
Would you like a newspaper to read?

189
00:12:22,255 --> 00:12:25,031
WOMAN: Yes, please. Thank you.

190
00:12:38,138 --> 00:12:39,811
(SHIP HORN SOUNDING)

191
00:13:12,906 --> 00:13:14,283
(CELL PHONE BEEPS)

192
00:13:52,345 --> 00:13:53,551
Passport?

193
00:14:59,512 --> 00:15:01,549
RUTH: This is an absolute scandal!

194
00:15:01,614 --> 00:15:02,615
Amelia Bly. Welcome.

195
00:15:02,682 --> 00:15:03,683
(DOOR SLAMMING)

196
00:15:03,750 --> 00:15:04,854
I'm Adam's assistant.

197
00:15:04,918 --> 00:15:08,627
Adam's in New York, unfortunately, 
and won't be back until later this afternoon.

198
00:15:08,688 --> 00:15:11,362
RUTH: Actually, forget I said that, 
it's bloody ridiculous!

199
00:15:11,424 --> 00:15:12,459
(DOOR SLAMS AGAIN)

200
00:15:12,525 --> 00:15:15,768
(CHUCKLES) Oh, dear. I'm so sorry. 
I'm afraid Ruth's having one of those days.

201
00:15:15,829 --> 00:15:17,399
If this isn't a good time, I could go to...

202
00:15:17,464 --> 00:15:19,671
No, no. She's keen to meet you.

203
00:15:20,467 --> 00:15:23,346
-Right. Shall we make a start? 
-Right.

204
00:15:25,171 --> 00:15:27,515
-How was your journey? 
-Long.

205
00:15:27,674 --> 00:15:29,244
AMELIA: We're a small team. 
GHOST: Thanks.

206
00:15:29,309 --> 00:15:30,686
AMELIA: This is Alice.

207
00:15:31,044 --> 00:15:33,354
Lucy's traveling with Adam.

208
00:15:33,513 --> 00:15:37,086
We need another pair of hands, but Adam 
couldn't bring himself to replace Mike.

209
00:15:37,150 --> 00:15:39,255
-They were together so long. 
-How long were you with him?

210
00:15:39,319 --> 00:15:41,731
AMELIA: Eight years. 
I'm an attachment from Number 10.

211
00:15:41,821 --> 00:15:43,425
Ah. Poor Number 10.

212
00:15:43,490 --> 00:15:44,935
Before I show you the manuscript,

213
00:15:44,991 --> 00:15:47,995
I need you to sign 
this confidentiality agreement.

214
00:15:52,532 --> 00:15:53,806
Sign here.

215
00:15:57,637 --> 00:15:58,911
And here.

216
00:16:00,707 --> 00:16:02,050
And here.

217
00:16:12,986 --> 00:16:15,159
GHOST: Wow, quite a place.

218
00:16:15,688 --> 00:16:17,326
Don't you get lonely at night?

219
00:16:17,457 --> 00:16:19,095
It's my husband I miss the most.

220
00:16:19,159 --> 00:16:21,332
Are you married? 
I noticed you don't wear a wedding ring.

221
00:16:21,394 --> 00:16:23,431
I can't, sadly. it's far too large.

222
00:16:23,496 --> 00:16:26,670
-it bleeps when I go through airport security. 
-Oh.

223
00:16:27,867 --> 00:16:29,278
Here we are.

224
00:16:30,136 --> 00:16:31,479
(ELECTRONIC BEEPING)

225
00:16:32,505 --> 00:16:36,681
The manuscript is not to be removed 
from this room. it's not to be copied.

226
00:16:38,244 --> 00:16:41,191
You have six hours 
before Adam gets in from New York.

227
00:16:41,247 --> 00:16:44,160
-Can you finish by then? 
-I'll try.

228
00:16:44,851 --> 00:16:47,195
I'll ask Dep to bring you up 
a sandwich for lunch.

229
00:16:47,253 --> 00:16:48,288
Thanks.

230
00:16:53,860 --> 00:16:54,998
Have fun.

231
00:17:02,535 --> 00:17:05,880
"Langs are Scottish folk, 
originally, and proud of it.

232
00:17:05,939 --> 00:17:10,388
"Our name is a derivation of 'long,' 
the Old English word for 'tall,'

233
00:17:10,443 --> 00:17:13,890
"and it is from north of the border 
that my forefathers hail."

234
00:17:14,581 --> 00:17:15,582
Fuck.

235
00:17:17,383 --> 00:17:19,693
"My great-grandfather, Ebenezer Lang,

236
00:17:19,752 --> 00:17:23,529
"was born in 1862 in Pitlochry, Scotland.

237
00:17:23,590 --> 00:17:25,570
"One of nine children, seven of them boys."

238
00:17:25,625 --> 00:17:28,401
"The American President 
was much taller than I had expected."

239
00:17:28,461 --> 00:17:29,633
(LAUGHING)

240
00:17:29,696 --> 00:17:32,700
"This year's European summit 
was particularly interesting."

241
00:17:32,765 --> 00:17:35,678
"I always found the Queen, in private, 
to have a delightful sense of humor."

242
00:17:54,687 --> 00:17:55,893
Thanks.

243
00:18:17,177 --> 00:18:18,679
(READING INDISTINCTLY)

244
00:18:19,712 --> 00:18:23,785
"I've always been an optimist. 
The present is where we live.

245
00:18:23,850 --> 00:18:27,730
"Ruth and I look forward to the future, 
whatever it may hold."

246
00:18:31,558 --> 00:18:32,969
As bad as that?

247
00:18:34,394 --> 00:18:35,498
Oh, hello.

248
00:18:36,896 --> 00:18:39,035
Well? How bad is it?

249
00:18:39,098 --> 00:18:40,634
You haven't read it?

250
00:18:40,867 --> 00:18:42,073
Not all of it.

251
00:18:42,235 --> 00:18:45,341
-Well, let's just say it needs some work. 
-How much work?

252
00:18:45,405 --> 00:18:48,511
Well, all the words are there. 
They're just in the wrong order.

253
00:18:50,043 --> 00:18:53,047
Come on. You look like you need a break.

254
00:18:56,849 --> 00:18:58,351
You were my idea.

255
00:18:59,118 --> 00:19:00,461
I was?

256
00:19:00,787 --> 00:19:02,926
You wrote Christy Costello's memoirs, 
didn't you?

257
00:19:03,089 --> 00:19:04,625
You read those?

258
00:19:04,791 --> 00:19:08,136
We stayed at his house in Mustique, 
last winter.

259
00:19:08,528 --> 00:19:09,666
The book was beside the bed.

260
00:19:09,729 --> 00:19:11,504
-I'm embarrassed. 
-No, why?

261
00:19:11,564 --> 00:19:14,875
It was brilliant, in a horrible sort of way.

262
00:19:15,234 --> 00:19:20,047
How you turned his ramblings 
into something vaguely coherent.

263
00:19:20,740 --> 00:19:24,916
I said to Adam, "Here's the guy 
to write your book, not Mike."

264
00:19:27,080 --> 00:19:30,027
(SIGHS) God, I miss home.

265
00:19:34,787 --> 00:19:37,996
It's like being married 
to Napoleon on St. Helena.

266
00:19:38,257 --> 00:19:41,101
-Why don't you go back to London? 
-RUTH: I don't feel I can leave him alone.

267
00:19:41,160 --> 00:19:43,606
There's something not quite right 
with him at the moment.

268
00:19:44,998 --> 00:19:48,275
Amelia told me he was very upset 
at the death of Michael McAra.

269
00:19:48,334 --> 00:19:49,677
Oh, she did, did she?

270
00:19:50,136 --> 00:19:54,516
Quite when Mrs. Bly became the expert 
on my husband's emotions, I'm not sure.

271
00:19:58,311 --> 00:20:00,484
Losing Mike was a blow, of course,

272
00:20:01,748 --> 00:20:03,284
but it's not just that.

273
00:20:03,449 --> 00:20:08,364
It's having to relive everything, 
year by year, for this bloody book.

274
00:20:11,491 --> 00:20:12,799
Oh, dear.

275
00:20:14,160 --> 00:20:17,107
You must be wondering 
what you've let yourself in for.

276
00:20:19,332 --> 00:20:22,279
Fine, fine. I'll tell him.

277
00:20:22,335 --> 00:20:23,939
They're just about to land.

278
00:20:24,103 --> 00:20:25,138
On Thursday, he's in Chicago.

279
00:20:25,204 --> 00:20:27,377
Actually, I think I'll go and meet him.

280
00:20:27,707 --> 00:20:30,620
Amelia can stay here 
and polish her nails or something.

281
00:20:30,777 --> 00:20:32,779
Why don't you come, say hello?

282
00:20:32,945 --> 00:20:36,984
Fine. I'll travel in the backup car. 
I can do my nails in there.

283
00:21:24,397 --> 00:21:25,535
(CHUCKLING)

284
00:21:25,598 --> 00:21:26,838
Hi, darling.

285
00:21:26,899 --> 00:21:28,845
-How was New York? 
-Short and sweet.

286
00:21:28,901 --> 00:21:31,040
Hi, Barry. Hi, Amelia.

287
00:21:32,171 --> 00:21:33,980
Hello. Who are you?

288
00:21:34,040 --> 00:21:35,212
I'm your ghost.

289
00:21:36,109 --> 00:21:37,144
Right.

290
00:21:37,210 --> 00:21:39,588
Don't worry. He isn't always such a jerk.

291
00:21:49,188 --> 00:21:51,327
This place really comes alive at night.

292
00:22:20,953 --> 00:22:23,832
You'll be with us for four weeks, 
is that right?

293
00:22:23,890 --> 00:22:24,925
I'm afraid so.

294
00:22:24,991 --> 00:22:27,369
And the bill goes directly 
to the Rhinehart Corporation?

295
00:22:27,426 --> 00:22:28,427
Good.

296
00:22:28,494 --> 00:22:30,906
That doesn't include the mini-bar.

297
00:22:41,007 --> 00:22:42,145
(SNORING)

298
00:23:14,774 --> 00:23:17,015
All right. He's ready for you.

299
00:23:21,113 --> 00:23:22,615
How's your hotel? Quiet?

300
00:23:22,682 --> 00:23:23,786
Monastic.

301
00:23:23,849 --> 00:23:26,090
That's nice. No distractions.

302
00:23:34,227 --> 00:23:35,706
Thanks, love.

303
00:23:37,697 --> 00:23:40,507
Hi, man. You ready to start?

304
00:23:40,566 --> 00:23:41,909
Absolutely.

305
00:23:44,670 --> 00:23:46,047
(ELECTRONIC BEEPING)

306
00:23:58,451 --> 00:24:00,692
-GHOST: Is the manuscript loaded on this? 
-It is.

307
00:24:00,753 --> 00:24:01,754
Can I have it?

308
00:24:01,821 --> 00:24:03,767
AMELIA: I'm sorry, 
that would be a security risk.

309
00:24:04,657 --> 00:24:06,500
You mean I've got to retype 
the whole manuscript?

310
00:24:06,559 --> 00:24:08,937
Have you really got my entire book 
on that little thing?

311
00:24:08,995 --> 00:24:10,668
We can get 100 books on it, Adam.

312
00:24:10,730 --> 00:24:13,939
And it can be copied in a flash. 
That's the trouble.

313
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:15,240
Amazing.

314
00:24:16,068 --> 00:24:18,708
You know the worst thing about my life? 
You get so out of touch.

315
00:24:18,771 --> 00:24:22,014
Everything's done for you. 
You don't drive, you don't carry money.

316
00:24:22,074 --> 00:24:25,385
If I need cash, 
I have to borrow it from the protection boys.

317
00:24:26,178 --> 00:24:28,385
This is the kind of details 
we need in the memoirs.

318
00:24:28,447 --> 00:24:31,621
I couldn't put that in. 
People would think I was a complete idiot.

319
00:24:31,684 --> 00:24:35,962
No, not at all. No, this shows what it's like 
being Prime Minister.

320
00:24:36,022 --> 00:24:37,831
That's exactly 
what the readers want to know.

321
00:24:37,890 --> 00:24:41,463
How does it feel to run a country? 
How does it feel to be so cut off?

322
00:24:41,527 --> 00:24:43,564
How does it feel to be so hated?

323
00:24:43,629 --> 00:24:44,972
Thanks a lot.

324
00:24:45,031 --> 00:24:46,806
(STAMMERS) And so loved.

325
00:24:46,866 --> 00:24:48,436
Amelia, what do you think?

326
00:24:48,501 --> 00:24:51,072
I think I should leave you two alone.

327
00:24:57,009 --> 00:24:58,079
(DOOR CLOSES)

328
00:24:59,779 --> 00:25:02,521
So, how do we go about this?

329
00:25:03,616 --> 00:25:05,220
I interview you.

330
00:25:06,085 --> 00:25:08,031
I turn your answers into prose.

331
00:25:08,087 --> 00:25:11,068
Here and there, I'll add linking passages, 
imitating your voice.

332
00:25:11,123 --> 00:25:12,227
Okay.

333
00:25:13,659 --> 00:25:16,299
-You heard about Mike? 
-Yes. I'm sorry.

334
00:25:19,832 --> 00:25:22,472
We should put in 
something nice about him.

335
00:25:22,535 --> 00:25:24,481
I think his mother would like that.

336
00:25:24,537 --> 00:25:25,914
Of course.

337
00:25:29,342 --> 00:25:33,017
Well, um, the first thing that struck me was,

338
00:25:33,279 --> 00:25:35,088
you became such a successful politician

339
00:25:35,147 --> 00:25:37,753
precisely because 
you didn't appear to be a politician.

340
00:25:37,817 --> 00:25:40,457
It's certainly not something I wanted to do 
when I was younger.

341
00:25:40,519 --> 00:25:43,159
I thought most student politicians 
were complete nerds.

342
00:25:43,222 --> 00:25:46,499
Well, I'm with you there. 
So, what turned you on to politics?

343
00:25:46,559 --> 00:25:47,629
(CHUCKLES)

344
00:25:47,993 --> 00:25:49,802
Turned me on, indeed.

345
00:25:51,964 --> 00:25:57,141
Let's see, I was 23, something like that, 
a couple of years out of Cambridge.

346
00:25:58,170 --> 00:26:01,811
And I remember it was a Sunday afternoon, 
it was raining.

347
00:26:01,874 --> 00:26:05,583
I was still in bed. 
And someone starts knocking at the door.

348
00:26:06,846 --> 00:26:09,520
And, you know, 
I'd been out the night before

349
00:26:09,582 --> 00:26:12,119
and had a few drinks and what have you.

350
00:26:12,184 --> 00:26:14,994
So, I get the pillow and I put It 
over my head, and it starts up again.

351
00:26:15,054 --> 00:26:16,590
Knock, knock, knock, knock!

352
00:26:16,656 --> 00:26:20,627
And I get up, I'm swearing, 
I go to the door and there's this girl.

353
00:26:20,693 --> 00:26:24,607
She's soaking wet, but she just launches 
into this speech about the local elections.

354
00:26:24,664 --> 00:26:26,200
And that's it.

355
00:26:27,933 --> 00:26:30,209
-I'm in love. 
-And this is Ruth?

356
00:26:30,970 --> 00:26:32,608
This is Ruth.

357
00:26:33,806 --> 00:26:37,253
And the only way I can see her again 
is to join the party and hand out leaflets.

358
00:26:37,309 --> 00:26:38,788
This is great.

359
00:26:39,745 --> 00:26:40,849
You want to use this?

360
00:26:40,913 --> 00:26:43,655
Use it? I think we should open 
the whole book like this.

361
00:26:43,716 --> 00:26:45,593
"I went into politics out of love,

362
00:26:45,651 --> 00:26:49,827
"not love for a party or an ideology, 
but out of love for a woman."

363
00:26:51,657 --> 00:26:53,659
Could you transcribe this 
as quickly as possible, please?

364
00:26:53,726 --> 00:26:55,069
Of course.

365
00:26:55,594 --> 00:26:56,937
-Thanks. 
-How's it going?

366
00:26:56,996 --> 00:26:58,907
Pretty well. He keeps calling me "man."

367
00:26:58,965 --> 00:27:02,003
He always does that 
when he can't remember someone's name.

368
00:27:02,068 --> 00:27:04,378
There are sandwiches in the kitchen.

369
00:27:17,717 --> 00:27:18,957
(INAUDIBLE)

370
00:28:10,436 --> 00:28:11,676
(ELECTRONIC BEEPING)

371
00:28:49,375 --> 00:28:50,581
(METALLIC CLANGING)

372
00:28:51,210 --> 00:28:52,280
(ALARM WAILING)

373
00:29:02,688 --> 00:29:03,758
(GRUNTING)

374
00:29:03,923 --> 00:29:05,493
Oh, shit.

375
00:29:06,992 --> 00:29:08,300
It's awful.

376
00:29:08,360 --> 00:29:10,340
I'm sorry, sir. 
I didn't realize there was anyone up there.

377
00:29:10,396 --> 00:29:11,898
What on earth is going on?

378
00:29:11,964 --> 00:29:14,570
It's just a security drill, sir. 
We have it once a week.

379
00:29:14,633 --> 00:29:17,341
So, there you are. 
I'd rather lost track of you.

380
00:29:17,403 --> 00:29:19,542
I'm a big boy now. 
Can't keep your eye on me all the time.

381
00:29:19,605 --> 00:29:22,108
Don't wander around on your own. 
The security boys don't like it.

382
00:29:22,174 --> 00:29:23,346
Gotcha.

383
00:29:26,378 --> 00:29:29,723
-Did you win? 
-Didn't play tennis. Gym.

384
00:29:32,151 --> 00:29:35,098
Gym? What's he in training for? 
The Olympics?

385
00:29:36,689 --> 00:29:38,600
Here's your transcript.

386
00:29:43,796 --> 00:29:44,900
(COMPUTER CHIMES)

387
00:29:46,165 --> 00:29:48,008
Cambridge. Let's talk about that.

388
00:29:49,535 --> 00:29:50,673
Sorry? Um...

389
00:29:51,370 --> 00:29:52,747
Cambridge?

390
00:29:54,240 --> 00:29:57,346
It was such a long time ago, 
I can hardly remember.

391
00:29:57,409 --> 00:29:58,979
You did a lot of acting?

392
00:29:59,645 --> 00:30:00,749
Some.

393
00:30:01,647 --> 00:30:04,423
It must have been good training 
for politics, acting?

394
00:30:04,984 --> 00:30:06,861
It was a good way to meet girls.

395
00:30:06,919 --> 00:30:09,422
Let's not put that in, by the way, okay?

396
00:30:09,488 --> 00:30:12,196
Still, acting must have been 
very important to you.

397
00:30:12,257 --> 00:30:13,634
Okay, let's say I enjoyed it.

398
00:30:13,692 --> 00:30:15,694
You know, you go on the stage, 
pretend to be somebody else,

399
00:30:15,761 --> 00:30:18,435
and people actually applaud you for it.

400
00:30:18,497 --> 00:30:19,976
Good, that's more like it. Let's put that in.

401
00:30:20,032 --> 00:30:21,067
-No. 
-Why not?

402
00:30:21,133 --> 00:30:23,010
Because these are the memoirs 
of a Prime Minister.

403
00:30:23,068 --> 00:30:25,309
And whenever my opponents were stuck 
with something to hit me with,

404
00:30:25,371 --> 00:30:27,442
they always said I was a bloody actor!

405
00:30:27,506 --> 00:30:30,851
Do you know what the Times of London 
said the day I resigned?

406
00:30:30,910 --> 00:30:32,856
"Kindly leave the stage."

407
00:30:32,912 --> 00:30:36,519
So, no, we won't dwell, if you don't mind, 
on my student days as an actor.

408
00:30:36,582 --> 00:30:39,426
We leave it exactly the way Mike wrote it.

409
00:30:41,320 --> 00:30:42,526
Would you like to take 
a break for a minute?

410
00:30:42,588 --> 00:30:45,933
Actually, that would be a good idea, 
thank you. I need to make a call.

411
00:30:54,967 --> 00:30:55,968
(DOOR OPENS)

412
00:30:59,872 --> 00:31:01,408
AMELIA: What a bastard.

413
00:31:04,677 --> 00:31:06,156
Look at this.

414
00:31:10,950 --> 00:31:13,487
"Former British Foreign Secretary 
Richard Rycart

415
00:31:13,552 --> 00:31:16,624
"has asked the International Criminal Court 
in The Hague to investigate allegations

416
00:31:16,689 --> 00:31:18,726
"that the former British Prime Minister 
Adam Lang

417
00:31:18,791 --> 00:31:21,397
"ordered the illegal handover 
of terrorist suspects

418
00:31:21,994 --> 00:31:23,564
"for torture by the CIA."

419
00:31:23,629 --> 00:31:24,767
(PHONE RINGING)

420
00:31:24,830 --> 00:31:26,002
Don't!

421
00:31:26,065 --> 00:31:27,408
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

422
00:31:29,201 --> 00:31:30,771
The pack is on the move.

423
00:31:30,836 --> 00:31:32,679
Unplug all the phones.

424
00:31:33,205 --> 00:31:36,209
Is Ruth still out walking? 
Shit! She is, isn't she?

425
00:31:36,275 --> 00:31:38,653
-Barry! Barry! 
-Yeah.

426
00:31:38,711 --> 00:31:42,215
Would you please find Mrs. Lang 
and get her back here as soon as you can?

427
00:31:42,281 --> 00:31:43,919
-Right. 
-AMELIA: Let's go.

428
00:31:45,050 --> 00:31:46,723
-Rycart has made a statement. 
-Yes, I know.

429
00:31:46,785 --> 00:31:48,128
-He just called me. 
-AMELIA: it's unbelievable.

430
00:31:48,187 --> 00:31:50,463
He wanted very much to let me know 
it was nothing personal.

431
00:31:50,522 --> 00:31:52,559
He wanted very, very much to tell me 
that it was only

432
00:31:52,624 --> 00:31:56,538
because of his well-known stand 
on human rights

433
00:31:56,595 --> 00:31:58,905
that he couldn't keep quiet any longer.

434
00:31:58,964 --> 00:32:02,502
"His well-known stand on human rights." 
Dear God!

435
00:32:08,841 --> 00:32:11,583
-Sorry to lose my temper earlier. 
-Forget it.

436
00:32:13,145 --> 00:32:15,056
And have you told her?

437
00:32:15,547 --> 00:32:18,027
ADAM: Yes. Just called her. 
AMELIA: And how did she take it?

438
00:32:18,083 --> 00:32:20,359
Sorry, Adam. This is running on AP.

439
00:32:22,388 --> 00:32:24,163
"According to sources in The Hague,

440
00:32:24,223 --> 00:32:27,397
"the prosecutor's office 
of the International Criminal Court

441
00:32:27,459 --> 00:32:29,370
"will issue a statement in the morning."

442
00:32:29,428 --> 00:32:30,736
AMELIA: Oh, Adam.

443
00:32:31,830 --> 00:32:33,207
Thank you, Alice.

444
00:32:33,265 --> 00:32:36,439
Why weren't we given some warning 
of this? Where's Downing Street?

445
00:32:36,502 --> 00:32:37,640
The phones are disconnected.

446
00:32:37,703 --> 00:32:39,239
Switch is probably 
trying to get through now.

447
00:32:39,304 --> 00:32:43,548
Now? What freaking use is now? 
What are you people doing?

448
00:32:43,609 --> 00:32:44,781
I mean, you're not telling me that

449
00:32:44,843 --> 00:32:46,516
the Cabinet Office 
didn't know this was coming?

450
00:32:46,578 --> 00:32:49,752
The war crimes court doesn't warn 
a suspect who's under investigation.

451
00:32:49,815 --> 00:32:52,227
That's what Adam is now, a suspect?

452
00:32:52,284 --> 00:32:53,558
You need to call Sid Kroll.

453
00:32:53,619 --> 00:32:55,656
I think we should call London first.

454
00:32:55,721 --> 00:32:59,225
Adam! If it suits them, 
they will hang you out to dry.

455
00:32:59,291 --> 00:33:01,430
-You need a lawyer. Call Sid. 
-(ADAM SIGHS)

456
00:33:02,861 --> 00:33:05,705
-Get Sid on the line. 
-What about the media?

457
00:33:05,764 --> 00:33:08,244
Issue a holding statement, something short.

458
00:33:08,300 --> 00:33:10,109
This is when we need Mike.

459
00:33:10,169 --> 00:33:11,944
I'll write something.

460
00:33:12,004 --> 00:33:14,382
Let him do it. 
He's supposed to be the writer.

461
00:33:14,440 --> 00:33:16,750
-Hang on a minute. 
-ADAM: I should sound confident.

462
00:33:16,809 --> 00:33:20,256
Not defensive, that'd be fatal. 
But I shouldn't be cocky.

463
00:33:20,312 --> 00:33:22,019
No bitterness, no anger, and don't say

464
00:33:22,080 --> 00:33:25,527
I'm pleased at this opportunity 
to clear my name or any balls like that.

465
00:33:25,584 --> 00:33:27,928
So, you're not defensive, 
but you're not cocky.

466
00:33:27,986 --> 00:33:29,590
You're not angry, but you're not pleased?

467
00:33:29,655 --> 00:33:32,261
-ADAM: That's it. 
-Then what exactly are you?

468
00:33:32,324 --> 00:33:33,462
(LAUGHING)

469
00:33:35,394 --> 00:33:36,634
Told you he was funny.

470
00:33:36,695 --> 00:33:39,539
I've always been a passionate supporter...

471
00:33:39,598 --> 00:33:41,100
No, scrub that.

472
00:33:41,700 --> 00:33:44,943
I've always been 
a strong, no, committed supporter

473
00:33:45,003 --> 00:33:48,450
of the work 
of the International Criminal Court. Has he?

474
00:33:48,841 --> 00:33:50,149
You're the writer.

475
00:33:50,209 --> 00:33:52,815
The struggle against terror is too important

476
00:33:52,878 --> 00:33:56,018
to be used for the purposes 
of personal revenge.

477
00:33:56,715 --> 00:34:00,026
Very good. 
You could be the new Mike McAra.

478
00:34:00,118 --> 00:34:01,358
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

479
00:34:01,820 --> 00:34:03,731
-Hello? 
-JOHN: John Maddox.

480
00:34:03,789 --> 00:34:07,566
This is gonna be big. 
This can only be good for us.

481
00:34:07,626 --> 00:34:10,334
-Could be. 
-Here's the first chapter right here.

482
00:34:10,395 --> 00:34:11,635
Okay.

483
00:34:11,697 --> 00:34:13,802
What've you covered so far?

484
00:34:13,966 --> 00:34:15,104
Um...

485
00:34:15,734 --> 00:34:18,078
The early years, childhood, university.

486
00:34:18,136 --> 00:34:20,980
All right, forget that crap. 
Get him focused on the war crimes.

487
00:34:21,039 --> 00:34:23,815
And he can't talk to anybody else, all right?

488
00:34:23,876 --> 00:34:25,719
-Right. 
-It's gotta be our exclusive.

489
00:34:25,777 --> 00:34:27,450
Any chance of you 
finishing the manuscript sooner?

490
00:34:27,513 --> 00:34:28,514
Sooner?

491
00:34:28,580 --> 00:34:30,321
Yeah, yeah, sooner.

492
00:34:30,983 --> 00:34:32,428
Well, how much sooner?

493
00:34:32,484 --> 00:34:34,361
I'm thinking two weeks.

494
00:34:35,721 --> 00:34:36,927
Jesus.

495
00:34:37,689 --> 00:34:40,295
Look, I know it's tough, 
but if anyone can do it, you can.

496
00:34:40,359 --> 00:34:42,703
I'm relying on you. We'll talk.

497
00:34:42,761 --> 00:34:43,899
(DISCONNECTS)

498
00:34:50,135 --> 00:34:51,205
Shit.

499
00:34:56,575 --> 00:34:57,883
I'd never have guessed you smoked.

500
00:34:57,943 --> 00:35:01,652
I only allow myself one 
at times of great stress or contentment.

501
00:35:01,713 --> 00:35:04,159
-And which is this? 
-Very funny.

502
00:35:04,216 --> 00:35:06,560
Maddox just called. He wants the book 
in two weeks instead of four.

503
00:35:06,618 --> 00:35:07,858
Christ. Good luck.

504
00:35:07,920 --> 00:35:11,458
Yeah, I wouldn't mind a lift back to my 
hotel. I could get on with some work there.

505
00:35:11,523 --> 00:35:13,002
You're not planning on 
taking that manuscript

506
00:35:13,058 --> 00:35:14,935
-out of here, are you? 
-Course not.

507
00:35:14,993 --> 00:35:17,872
Because you do realize 
how serious this is getting, don't you?

508
00:35:17,930 --> 00:35:20,911
-You can search me, if you like. 
-That won't be necessary.

509
00:35:22,568 --> 00:35:26,175
All right. Fetch your stuff. 
I'll get one of the boys to take you.

510
00:35:26,872 --> 00:35:29,853
Mr. Lang insisted he had always been 
a committed supporter

511
00:35:29,908 --> 00:35:32,889
of the work 
of the International Criminal Court.

512
00:35:32,945 --> 00:35:34,549
Mr. Lang added, quote,

513
00:35:34,613 --> 00:35:36,957
"The struggle against terror 
is too important

514
00:35:37,015 --> 00:35:39,621
"to be used for the purposes 
of personal revenge."

515
00:35:39,685 --> 00:35:41,665
-Same again, sir? 
-This is being widely interpreted as...

516
00:35:41,720 --> 00:35:43,165
-Yes, thanks. 
-...an attack on the former British

517
00:35:43,222 --> 00:35:46,726
Foreign Secretary Richard Rycart, 
who has asked...

518
00:35:46,792 --> 00:35:47,964
Could we change the channel?

519
00:35:48,026 --> 00:35:50,028
-Sure. 
-Thanks.

520
00:35:50,095 --> 00:35:53,565
At issue is the practice 
of so-called waterboarding,

521
00:35:53,632 --> 00:35:55,771
an interrogation technique 
considered a war...

522
00:35:56,401 --> 00:35:57,744
(MALE ANNOUNCER CHATTERING)

523
00:35:58,003 --> 00:36:00,882
-Something to eat? 
-What've you got?

524
00:36:00,939 --> 00:36:04,512
-Club sandwich. Clam chowder. 
-Chowder will be fine.

525
00:36:07,079 --> 00:36:08,581
MAN: You're English?

526
00:36:11,783 --> 00:36:13,285
GHOST: And so are you.

527
00:36:13,819 --> 00:36:15,230
Indeed I am.

528
00:36:15,888 --> 00:36:18,698
-You here on a holiday? 
-No, I'm working.

529
00:36:18,757 --> 00:36:20,532
So, what's your line?

530
00:36:20,792 --> 00:36:22,999
Just this and that. Excuse me.

531
00:36:25,597 --> 00:36:28,043
I hear Adam Lang's on the island.

532
00:36:31,436 --> 00:36:32,744
Is he?

533
00:36:32,804 --> 00:36:34,147
So I hear.

534
00:36:35,941 --> 00:36:37,818
You don't happen to know 
his whereabouts, do you?

535
00:36:37,876 --> 00:36:38,911
No.

536
00:36:40,112 --> 00:36:42,524
No, I'm afraid not. If you don't mind.

537
00:36:43,148 --> 00:36:45,754
MALE ANNOUNCER: 
Raymond to Naslund and to Mattias Ohlund.

538
00:36:45,817 --> 00:36:49,424
A slap pass to Lukas Krajicek. 
He's in trouble against

539
00:36:50,455 --> 00:36:52,867
Barret Jackman and the referee...

540
00:36:53,792 --> 00:36:55,032
Asshole.

541
00:36:55,127 --> 00:36:58,631
...and Ohlund can't hold it in again, 
and this power play is just about over.

542
00:36:58,697 --> 00:37:01,177
Keith Tkachuk almost set to come back on.

543
00:37:37,703 --> 00:37:38,909
Hello?

544
00:37:41,540 --> 00:37:42,644
(DINGS BELL)

545
00:37:49,214 --> 00:37:50,887
-Can I help you? 
-Hi.

546
00:37:50,949 --> 00:37:54,863
(STAMMERING) Yeah, can you tell me, 
has anyone gone up to my room?

547
00:37:54,920 --> 00:37:55,990
No, sir.

548
00:37:56,054 --> 00:37:58,159
-Did anyone ask for me? 
-No.

549
00:38:00,926 --> 00:38:03,463
What about that other guest? The, um...

550
00:38:04,229 --> 00:38:06,300
There's an Englishman.

551
00:38:06,365 --> 00:38:09,073
You're the only guest in the hotel, sir.

552
00:38:09,735 --> 00:38:11,009
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

553
00:38:23,715 --> 00:38:24,785
-Hello? 
-AMELIA: You need to check out

554
00:38:24,850 --> 00:38:26,625
of the hotel immediately.

555
00:38:26,685 --> 00:38:28,892
Things have changed. A car is on its way.

556
00:38:28,954 --> 00:38:30,092
What?

557
00:38:30,322 --> 00:38:31,767
See you then.

558
00:38:32,724 --> 00:38:33,930
Hello?

559
00:38:34,059 --> 00:38:35,129
(CAR HORN HONKING)

560
00:38:35,327 --> 00:38:36,499
(DIAL TONE SOUNDS)

561
00:38:39,431 --> 00:38:40,739
(TRUCK BEEPING)

562
00:38:49,408 --> 00:38:51,479
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

563
00:39:03,088 --> 00:39:04,965
-MAN: Okay. 
-Just check on that. Okay?

564
00:39:12,497 --> 00:39:15,273
-it's getting big, huh? 
-So I see.

565
00:39:16,268 --> 00:39:17,872
Who're you with?

566
00:39:19,071 --> 00:39:20,607
I'm on my own.

567
00:39:23,842 --> 00:39:26,083
Oh, sod it. Here we go again.

568
00:39:26,144 --> 00:39:27,748
(PEOPLE CLAMORING)

569
00:39:29,181 --> 00:39:30,455
(PHONE RINGING)

570
00:39:33,151 --> 00:39:36,064
RICK: You've reached the office 
of Rick Ricardelli. Leave a message.

571
00:39:36,121 --> 00:39:38,863
Hi, Rick. 
Now they want the book in two weeks.

572
00:39:39,391 --> 00:39:41,371
Thanks for getting me this job.

573
00:39:41,426 --> 00:39:44,202
Can't talk. 
Some peace protesters are trying to kill me.

574
00:39:44,262 --> 00:39:48,074
You're working for a murderer! 
You're working for a murderer!

575
00:39:49,735 --> 00:39:52,181
WOMAN: Liar! Liar! Liar!

576
00:39:54,005 --> 00:39:55,075
(EXHALES)

577
00:39:57,809 --> 00:39:59,880
-Are you ill? 
-No, I'm aging.

578
00:40:00,645 --> 00:40:03,182
This place is Shangri-La in reverse.

579
00:40:03,615 --> 00:40:05,754
AMELIA: I tried to call you 
several times last night.

580
00:40:05,817 --> 00:40:06,955
You didn't answer.

581
00:40:07,018 --> 00:40:08,759
GHOST: I forgot to charge my mobile phone.

582
00:40:08,820 --> 00:40:11,027
Really? And the hotel phone?

583
00:40:11,089 --> 00:40:12,261
I'm a heavy sleeper.

584
00:40:12,324 --> 00:40:14,861
Well, you can do your heavy sleeping here 
from now on.

585
00:40:14,926 --> 00:40:17,099
-Here? 
-AMELIA: We're under siege.

586
00:40:17,162 --> 00:40:19,665
You can't run the media gauntlet every day.

587
00:40:19,731 --> 00:40:24,202
Eventually, they'll discover who you are. 
And that would be horrid for you.

588
00:40:32,844 --> 00:40:34,653
So, this is where you put the granny.

589
00:40:34,713 --> 00:40:35,748
No.

590
00:40:36,415 --> 00:40:38,759
This is where we put Mike McAra.

591
00:40:45,023 --> 00:40:48,766
We haven't had a chance to clear it yet. 
The sheets have been changed, though.

592
00:40:48,827 --> 00:40:51,467
Actually, I make it a rule 
never to stay in a client's house.

593
00:40:51,530 --> 00:40:54,602
But now you can have constant access 
to the manuscript.

594
00:40:54,666 --> 00:40:55,736
Isn't that what you want?

595
00:40:55,800 --> 00:40:58,110
Besides, Sid Kroll 
will be arriving any minute.

596
00:40:58,170 --> 00:41:01,583
Why don't you settle in, 
and then come up and join us?

597
00:41:01,640 --> 00:41:04,280
-You're practically one of us now. 
-l am?

598
00:41:04,342 --> 00:41:08,415
You drafted the statement yesterday. 
That makes you an accomplice.

599
00:41:10,749 --> 00:41:11,853
(DOOR CLOSES)

600
00:41:12,317 --> 00:41:14,854
So, here's the score. You're not being 
charged, you're not being arrested.

601
00:41:14,920 --> 00:41:16,297
None of this is gonna amount 
to a hill of beans.

602
00:41:16,354 --> 00:41:18,163
The only thing the prosecutor is asking for

603
00:41:18,223 --> 00:41:20,260
is permission to launch 
a formal investigation.

604
00:41:20,325 --> 00:41:22,566
-investigating me for what? 
-Connie?

605
00:41:22,627 --> 00:41:24,538
Either crimes against humanity 
or war crimes.

606
00:41:24,596 --> 00:41:27,304
Well, that's absurd. 
it's not exactly genocide.

607
00:41:27,365 --> 00:41:30,278
"Under Article 25, 
a person shall be guilty of a war crime

608
00:41:30,335 --> 00:41:33,009
"if that person facilitates the commission 
of such a crime

609
00:41:33,071 --> 00:41:35,745
"or aids, abets or otherwise assists 
in its commission."

610
00:41:35,807 --> 00:41:38,515
-That's rather sweeping. 
-Well, if it's any comfort,

611
00:41:38,576 --> 00:41:42,046
you're in no jeopardy 
as long as you stay here, among friends.

612
00:41:42,113 --> 00:41:44,423
Are you saying 
I can't leave the United States?

613
00:41:44,482 --> 00:41:48,123
As your attorney, I strongly advise you 
not to travel to any country

614
00:41:48,186 --> 00:41:51,258
that recognizes the jurisdiction 
of the International Criminal Court.

615
00:41:51,323 --> 00:41:53,803
Well, just about every country in the world 
recognizes the ICC.

616
00:41:53,858 --> 00:41:55,030
America doesn't.

617
00:41:55,093 --> 00:41:56,731
-Who else? 
-SIDNEY: Josh?

618
00:41:56,795 --> 00:41:59,742
Iraq, China, North Korea, Indonesia, Israel.

619
00:42:01,733 --> 00:42:04,270
-And that's it? 
-JOSH: There are some parts of Africa.

620
00:42:04,336 --> 00:42:05,440
Wait!

621
00:42:05,503 --> 00:42:09,007
I wish to make a short statement. 
I won't be taking questions.

622
00:42:09,074 --> 00:42:11,520
This morning, I was granted power 
to investigate

623
00:42:11,576 --> 00:42:15,149
the former British Prime Minister, 
Mr. Adam Peter Bennett Lang,

624
00:42:15,213 --> 00:42:20,925
under Articles 7 and 8 of the 1998 Rome 
Statute of the International Criminal Court.

625
00:42:21,286 --> 00:42:24,392
I shall shortly be contacting Mr. Lang 
and the British government

626
00:42:24,456 --> 00:42:26,402
to ask for their full cooperation. Thank you.

627
00:42:31,730 --> 00:42:33,175
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

628
00:42:34,933 --> 00:42:35,968
Oh, God.

629
00:42:36,034 --> 00:42:38,446
Okay, we need to get you to Washington, 
Adam, right away.

630
00:42:38,503 --> 00:42:39,743
My plane is at the airport.

631
00:42:39,804 --> 00:42:42,080
We can get you in to see 
the Speaker of the House at lunchtime

632
00:42:42,140 --> 00:42:44,586
and have a photo-op 
with the Secretary of State in the afternoon.

633
00:42:44,643 --> 00:42:46,520
Won't it look as if I'm panicking?

634
00:42:46,578 --> 00:42:48,717
No, they'll both say 
that the meetings were fixed weeks ago.

635
00:42:48,780 --> 00:42:50,225
Well, what the hell 
are we supposed to be discussing?

636
00:42:50,282 --> 00:42:52,523
SIDNEY: AIDS? Poverty? Climate change?

637
00:42:52,584 --> 00:42:55,622
Who cares? The important thing 
is to show the world it's business as usual.

638
00:42:55,687 --> 00:42:58,827
-What do you think, Ruth? 
-l think it's a terrible idea.

639
00:42:58,890 --> 00:43:00,494
You'll look as though 
you're America's whipping boy,

640
00:43:00,559 --> 00:43:02,129
running crying home to daddy.

641
00:43:02,193 --> 00:43:04,867
-So, what would you do? 
-RUTH: Fly to London.

642
00:43:05,363 --> 00:43:07,274
The government will support you.

643
00:43:07,332 --> 00:43:11,610
"The British government 
will cooperate fully with the investigation."

644
00:43:12,003 --> 00:43:14,347
Really? And what makes you think that?

645
00:43:14,639 --> 00:43:17,313
I'm not thinking it, Ruth, I'm reading it.

646
00:43:17,842 --> 00:43:20,846
...believe we can now go live 
to the UN in New York,

647
00:43:20,912 --> 00:43:24,587
where the former British Foreign Secretary, 
Richard Rycart,

648
00:43:24,649 --> 00:43:26,356
is about to make a statement.

649
00:43:26,418 --> 00:43:29,763
I watched the announcement in The Hague 
today with great shock and sadness.

650
00:43:29,821 --> 00:43:32,233
Adam Lang was 
and is an old friend of mine.

651
00:43:32,290 --> 00:43:33,860
You cheeky bugger!

652
00:43:33,925 --> 00:43:37,270
I regret that he's chosen to bring this down 
to a personal level.

653
00:43:37,328 --> 00:43:40,002
This isn't personal. This is about justice.

654
00:43:40,432 --> 00:43:43,311
This is about making sure 
every political leader knows

655
00:43:43,368 --> 00:43:44,904
when they make a decision,

656
00:43:44,970 --> 00:43:47,814
they will be held to account 
by international law.

657
00:43:48,373 --> 00:43:49,374
Thank you.

658
00:43:49,441 --> 00:43:51,284
MALE REPORTER: 
If you're called to testify, sir, will you go?

659
00:43:51,343 --> 00:43:54,790
-RICHARD: Certainly, I'll go. 
-Of course you will, you little shit!

660
00:43:54,846 --> 00:43:57,087
That settles it. Washington it is.

661
00:43:57,482 --> 00:43:58,825
RUTH: I still say it'll look bad.

662
00:43:58,883 --> 00:44:01,762
Not as bad as being led away 
from Heathrow in handcuffs.

663
00:44:01,820 --> 00:44:03,060
It would show you had some guts.

664
00:44:03,121 --> 00:44:05,067
Well, then why the hell 
don't you just fly back without me?

665
00:44:05,123 --> 00:44:08,935
If the British government wants to hand me 
over to this kangaroo court, then sod them!

666
00:44:08,994 --> 00:44:11,235
I'll go where people want me.

667
00:44:12,297 --> 00:44:15,506
Amelia, tell the boys we're leaving. 
Have one of the girls pack me a bag.

668
00:44:15,567 --> 00:44:17,478
You'd better pack one for yourself.

669
00:44:17,535 --> 00:44:21,108
Why don't you share a suitcase? 
it's so much more convenient.

670
00:44:46,664 --> 00:44:49,975
I'll see you tomorrow. 
I'm sorry to abandon you.

671
00:44:50,535 --> 00:44:52,378
At least this might help sales.

672
00:44:52,504 --> 00:44:55,007
Perhaps Rhinehart's PR department 
organized the whole thing.

673
00:44:55,106 --> 00:44:56,176
(LAUGHS)

674
00:44:56,841 --> 00:44:59,481
Well, tell them to stop it, will you?

675
00:45:04,849 --> 00:45:08,661
Okay, people, 
remember, happy, happy faces.

676
00:45:16,061 --> 00:45:19,599
MALE REPORTER: So, just to summarize 
what we know so far, it's now official,

677
00:45:19,864 --> 00:45:22,504
the special prosecutor 
of the International War Crimes Court

678
00:45:22,567 --> 00:45:24,171
is to launch an investigation...

679
00:45:27,739 --> 00:45:31,152
...the special prosecutor announced 
she was going to investigate Mr. Lang,

680
00:45:31,209 --> 00:45:33,746
well, there was a big cheer, I can tell you.

681
00:45:33,812 --> 00:45:36,088
So, let's talk to some of these protesters.

682
00:45:36,147 --> 00:45:38,354
-You, sir, you're English, I believe. 
-I am.

683
00:45:38,416 --> 00:45:39,895
So, what brings you so far from home?

684
00:45:39,951 --> 00:45:43,489
My son. He was killed 
in one of Mr. Lang's illegal wars.

685
00:45:43,855 --> 00:45:47,200
Lang's never visited the injured. 
He's never apologized.

686
00:45:47,258 --> 00:45:50,432
I was in the British Army for 30 years. 
It's a disgrace!

687
00:45:50,662 --> 00:45:52,005
Thank you. 
Can I ask you the same question?

688
00:45:52,063 --> 00:45:53,064
(PROTESTERS CLAMORING)

689
00:45:53,131 --> 00:45:55,168
You're a murderer, Lang! 
You're a war criminal!

690
00:45:55,667 --> 00:45:57,578
CROWD: (CHANTING) 
Liar, liar, liar!

691
00:45:57,635 --> 00:45:59,546
WOMAN: (OVER BULLHORN) 
Lang, Lang, Lang!

692
00:45:59,604 --> 00:46:01,379
CROWD: Killer, killer, killer!

693
00:46:01,439 --> 00:46:05,114
WOMAN: Lang, Lang, Lang! 
CROWD: Liar, liar, liar!

694
00:46:05,443 --> 00:46:10,620
WOMAN: Lang, Lang, Lang! 
CROWD: Killer, killer, killer!

695
00:46:13,117 --> 00:46:14,255
MALE REPORTER 1: Over here, Mr. Lang!

696
00:46:14,319 --> 00:46:17,391
I apologize for keeping you waiting so long 
in the cold.

697
00:46:17,455 --> 00:46:19,799
MALE REPORTER 2: What's your reaction 
to Mr. Rycart's statement?

698
00:46:19,858 --> 00:46:24,136
I'd like to say a few words 
in response to the news from The Hague.

699
00:46:25,230 --> 00:46:30,145
These are strange times when 
those who stand for freedom and justice

700
00:46:30,201 --> 00:46:32,408
are accused of being criminals,

701
00:46:32,470 --> 00:46:36,680
while those who incite hatred 
and seek to destroy democracy

702
00:46:36,741 --> 00:46:39,813
-are treated as victims. 
-WOMAN: War criminal!

703
00:46:40,378 --> 00:46:43,518
Let me make one thing perfectly clear.

704
00:46:44,082 --> 00:46:48,224
While I have breath in my body, 
I shall fight terrorism...

705
00:46:48,286 --> 00:46:49,287
MAN: Liar!

706
00:46:49,387 --> 00:46:53,927
...whether it's on the battlefield 
or, if necessary, in the courts.

707
00:46:55,026 --> 00:46:56,130
Thank you very much.

708
00:46:56,194 --> 00:46:58,697
FEMALE REPORTER: Have you spoken 
to the President, Mr. Lang?

709
00:46:58,763 --> 00:46:59,901
(SWITCHES TV OFF)

710
00:46:59,964 --> 00:47:01,204
(RUTH SOBS)

711
00:47:13,745 --> 00:47:15,622
(SOBBING CONTINUES)

712
00:48:25,316 --> 00:48:26,989
Oh, for God's sake.

713
00:48:34,158 --> 00:48:35,364
God.

714
00:49:34,652 --> 00:49:35,790
Shit!

715
00:49:37,021 --> 00:49:38,125
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

716
00:49:38,690 --> 00:49:40,067
One minute!

717
00:49:44,295 --> 00:49:45,399
Yes?

718
00:49:48,866 --> 00:49:51,244
Sir? You want lunch?

719
00:49:51,302 --> 00:49:54,511
That would be great. 
Give me five minutes, thanks.

720
00:50:17,362 --> 00:50:18,705
P. Emmett?

721
00:50:37,081 --> 00:50:38,355
(DIALING)

722
00:50:46,090 --> 00:50:47,194
(PHONE RINGING)

723
00:50:53,898 --> 00:50:55,434
RICHARD: Richard Rycart.

724
00:50:57,535 --> 00:50:59,014
Who is this?

725
00:51:19,757 --> 00:51:20,963
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

726
00:51:35,273 --> 00:51:37,617
(SIGHING)

727
00:51:38,476 --> 00:51:40,114
-Dep? 
-Sir?

728
00:51:40,445 --> 00:51:42,425
Is there a map of the island 
that I could borrow?

729
00:51:42,480 --> 00:51:43,788
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

730
00:51:58,129 --> 00:52:00,109
Look. it's rain soon.

731
00:52:00,164 --> 00:52:02,542
I don't know. I think it will be all right.

732
00:52:02,600 --> 00:52:07,709
Why don't you take the car? 
it's for guests. Here's the key.

733
00:52:08,673 --> 00:52:11,711
-For our guests, it's very nice car. 
-Oh. Yes.

734
00:52:11,776 --> 00:52:14,689
Mr. McAra loved this car very, very much.

735
00:52:15,213 --> 00:52:18,717
Do you know... I'm gonna take the... 
I'm gonna take the bicycle. Thanks.

736
00:52:18,783 --> 00:52:20,456
This is... Just a moment, just a moment.

737
00:52:20,518 --> 00:52:25,331
It's rain. I give". 
I give you my hat and my gloves.

738
00:52:25,623 --> 00:52:27,762
-That's very kind, thank you. 
-Good luck for you.

739
00:52:27,825 --> 00:52:30,704
-Thank you. Thank you, yeah, bye. 
-Bye-bye.

740
00:53:01,892 --> 00:53:03,098
Just one moment.

741
00:53:03,160 --> 00:53:04,503
(CAR HORN HONKING)

742
00:53:37,528 --> 00:53:38,700
(THUNDERING)

743
00:54:26,310 --> 00:54:28,256
God, you frightened me.

744
00:54:28,512 --> 00:54:31,118
-You're British. 
-l am, yeah.

745
00:54:32,016 --> 00:54:34,462
It's okay, you can shelter. Sheltering's free.

746
00:54:34,519 --> 00:54:35,691
(DOG BARKING)

747
00:54:35,753 --> 00:54:37,699
No, no, no, no! Rosie, Rosie!

748
00:54:37,755 --> 00:54:39,701
In you go. In, in.

749
00:54:40,491 --> 00:54:41,629
Here.

750
00:54:44,996 --> 00:54:47,408
-So, you're British, huh? 
-Yeah.

751
00:54:47,798 --> 00:54:51,769
-You anything to do with this fellow, Lang? 
-In a way, yes.

752
00:54:51,836 --> 00:54:53,509
Seems intelligent.

753
00:54:53,571 --> 00:54:55,915
Now why did he go 
and get himself mixed up

754
00:54:55,973 --> 00:54:57,577
with that damn fool in the White House?

755
00:54:57,641 --> 00:54:59,416
Well, that's what everyone wants to know.

756
00:54:59,477 --> 00:55:02,481
What brings you to this part of the island?

757
00:55:02,813 --> 00:55:04,850
I'm sightseeing.

758
00:55:05,883 --> 00:55:08,762
Well, you sure picked a heck of a day for it.

759
00:55:08,819 --> 00:55:13,268
Someone I knew was found washed up 
on the beach there.

760
00:55:13,324 --> 00:55:16,862
-You mean the British guy from the ferry? 
-That's right.

761
00:55:17,495 --> 00:55:20,738
-Now that was a funny business. 
-What do you mean?

762
00:55:21,332 --> 00:55:24,836
No way should that current have carried him 
that far west.

763
00:55:24,902 --> 00:55:26,643
-No? 
-No way!

764
00:55:26,704 --> 00:55:28,206
Are you sure?

765
00:55:28,940 --> 00:55:31,147
I've lived here 54 years.

766
00:55:31,642 --> 00:55:33,485
Did you mention that to the police?

767
00:55:33,544 --> 00:55:38,152
The police? At my age, 
I've better things to do, young man.

768
00:55:38,883 --> 00:55:41,227
Annabeth's the one dealing with the police.

769
00:55:41,285 --> 00:55:42,457
Your wife?

770
00:55:42,520 --> 00:55:46,593
Annabeth Wurmbrand, 
Mars Wurmbrand's widow.

771
00:55:47,325 --> 00:55:50,499
She's the one 
who told them about the lights.

772
00:55:50,962 --> 00:55:54,307
-Lights? 
-The flashlights on the beach.

773
00:55:54,365 --> 00:55:58,313
-When? 
-The night the body was washed up.

774
00:56:00,838 --> 00:56:02,681
Could, could you, um...

775
00:56:03,574 --> 00:56:06,418
Could you point me in the direction 
of Mrs. Wurmbrand's house?

776
00:56:06,711 --> 00:56:08,520
Oh, sure. You just...

777
00:56:09,080 --> 00:56:11,583
Here. Follow it down the beach there.

778
00:56:11,649 --> 00:56:14,858
It's the house nearest the ocean. 
But she won't talk to you.

779
00:56:14,919 --> 00:56:17,695
-Why not? 
-She's in a coma.

780
00:56:18,522 --> 00:56:21,025
Fell down stairs a week ago.

781
00:56:21,425 --> 00:56:24,065
Been in a coma ever since.

782
00:57:05,669 --> 00:57:07,148
RUTH: Come down!

783
00:57:16,514 --> 00:57:17,925
Come down!

784
00:57:21,719 --> 00:57:24,222
Dep told me you were here!

785
00:57:24,655 --> 00:57:25,895
What?

786
00:57:25,956 --> 00:57:29,665
I said Dep told me you were here.

787
00:57:29,727 --> 00:57:32,765
We came to get you before the storm came. 
What are you doing?

788
00:57:32,830 --> 00:57:34,741
-Just taking the air. 
-No, really.

789
00:57:34,798 --> 00:57:37,278
I wanted to see 
where Mike McAra was found.

790
00:57:37,335 --> 00:57:38,439
Why?

791
00:57:38,502 --> 00:57:42,109
Adam's asked me 
to write something about him in the book.

792
00:57:42,673 --> 00:57:44,778
-Where's your bike? 
-Up there.

793
00:57:44,842 --> 00:57:47,448
Barry, will you come around with the car? 
We'll meet you out by the road.

794
00:57:47,511 --> 00:57:50,219
I can't do that, I'm afraid, Mrs. Lang. 
Have to stay with you at all times.

795
00:57:50,281 --> 00:57:52,192
For God's sake!

796
00:57:52,249 --> 00:57:54,126
If we meet any terrorists, I'll text you.

797
00:57:54,185 --> 00:57:56,631
All right, well, stay on the path. 
Don't speak to anyone.

798
00:57:56,687 --> 00:57:59,668
We won't talk to a soul, Officer, I promise.

799
00:58:03,160 --> 00:58:07,700
Poor Mike. I can't bear the idea of him 
ending up so far from home.

800
00:58:08,565 --> 00:58:12,012
I wonder if we'll ever know 
whether it was accident or suicide.

801
00:58:12,069 --> 00:58:14,447
Can't help you. I never met him.

802
00:58:15,873 --> 00:58:18,046
I suppose it doesn't really matter.

803
00:58:18,109 --> 00:58:22,148
He was drunk. He drowned. End of story.

804
00:58:23,480 --> 00:58:26,927
-What was he doing on the ferry? 
-No idea.

805
00:58:29,186 --> 00:58:31,860
Funeral's on Monday, in London.

806
00:58:34,091 --> 00:58:36,162
I'm thinking of going.

807
00:58:36,227 --> 00:58:37,433
One of us should put in an appearance,

808
00:58:37,495 --> 00:58:39,873
and it doesn't seem likely 
to be my husband.

809
00:58:39,930 --> 00:58:41,204
I thought you didn't want to leave him.

810
00:58:41,265 --> 00:58:44,769
Rather seems as though he's left me, 
wouldn't you say?

811
00:59:43,494 --> 00:59:44,564
(EXHALES)

812
00:59:48,499 --> 00:59:49,671
(DOOR OPENING)

813
00:59:56,907 --> 01:00:00,411
-Hello? 
-Sorry. I did knock. it's just me.

814
01:00:00,978 --> 01:00:04,357
-l brought you some dry clothes. 
-That's all right. I can manage.

815
01:00:04,415 --> 01:00:06,554
Dinner's in an hour, okay?

816
01:00:08,085 --> 01:00:11,498
Fine, thanks. For God's sake.

817
01:00:11,622 --> 01:00:13,067
(DISTANT THUNDERING)

818
01:00:31,875 --> 01:00:33,286
GHOST: "It was at the time 
of the London elections

819
01:00:33,343 --> 01:00:35,584
"that I first got to know Ruth.

820
01:00:35,646 --> 01:00:37,250
"She had gained a First at Oxford

821
01:00:37,314 --> 01:00:41,626
"and then done a year's postgraduate 
research as a Fulbright scholar."

822
01:00:42,219 --> 01:00:43,391
Ruth.

823
01:00:48,626 --> 01:00:49,832
Mmm.

824
01:00:50,194 --> 01:00:53,641
-Perfect fit. Now all you need is a drink. 
-What are we having?

825
01:00:53,697 --> 01:00:58,077
Biodynamic white wine from 
the Rhinehart Vinery in the Napa Valley.

826
01:01:01,939 --> 01:01:05,216
Rhinehart. He doesn't 
own a distillery, I suppose?

827
01:01:05,276 --> 01:01:06,482
(CHUCKLES)

828
01:01:08,746 --> 01:01:10,953
Mmm. Evening news.

829
01:01:12,116 --> 01:01:14,289
FEMALE NEWSREADER: ...for war crimes. 
Our political editor has more.

830
01:01:14,351 --> 01:01:15,694
Christ, we're the lead story.

831
01:01:16,820 --> 01:01:19,323
Pour us some more wine, will you?

832
01:01:19,990 --> 01:01:21,970
I may have to get drunk for a change.

833
01:01:22,693 --> 01:01:26,266
MALE NEWSREADER: In Washington, 
Mr. Lang received firm promises of support,

834
01:01:26,330 --> 01:01:29,504
both from congressional leaders 
and the Secretary of State,

835
01:01:29,566 --> 01:01:32,479
before going on to a private dinner tonight 
with the Vice President.

836
01:01:32,536 --> 01:01:36,040
Adam Lang has stood by America's side 
in the war against terror,

837
01:01:36,106 --> 01:01:39,178
and I'm proud to stand by his side 
this afternoon.

838
01:01:39,243 --> 01:01:41,746
-Adam, good to see you. 
-ADAM: Thank you.

839
01:01:41,812 --> 01:01:44,053
Thank you very much, indeed. 
It's good to see you.

840
01:01:44,114 --> 01:01:45,491
Don't grin.

841
01:01:46,317 --> 01:01:47,728
MALE NEWS READER: 
In Iraq, a suicide bomber...

842
01:01:47,785 --> 01:01:49,025
For God's sake!

843
01:01:49,086 --> 01:01:50,326
(SWITCHES TV OFF)

844
01:01:51,021 --> 01:01:52,364
(RUTH SIGHS)

845
01:01:53,757 --> 01:01:54,963
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

846
01:02:02,165 --> 01:02:03,303
Adam.

847
01:02:05,202 --> 01:02:07,978
Calling to find out how I think it went.

848
01:02:09,039 --> 01:02:11,713
-Let him sweat. 
-Does he always ask for your advice?

849
01:02:11,775 --> 01:02:13,254
Yes,

850
01:02:14,178 --> 01:02:16,454
and always usually takes it.

851
01:02:17,514 --> 01:02:19,016
Until lately.

852
01:02:21,251 --> 01:02:23,527
-Are you married? 
-Certainly not.

853
01:02:23,587 --> 01:02:25,624
-Gay? 
-No.

854
01:02:26,457 --> 01:02:29,233
-Did you have a... 
-l had a... Um...

855
01:02:29,293 --> 01:02:32,433
-What? Girlfriend? 
-Well, a bit more than that.

856
01:02:32,496 --> 01:02:33,839
Partner?

857
01:02:34,631 --> 01:02:36,008
A bit less than that.

858
01:02:36,066 --> 01:02:37,909
I don't know, 
40,000 years of human language

859
01:02:37,968 --> 01:02:40,141
and there's no word 
to describe our relationship.

860
01:02:40,204 --> 01:02:41,410
It was doomed.

861
01:02:41,471 --> 01:02:42,472
(CHUCKLES)

862
01:02:44,208 --> 01:02:46,245
Come on. Let's eat.

863
01:02:51,081 --> 01:02:53,357
-How's it going? 
-The book?

864
01:02:54,751 --> 01:02:57,789
-Well, it's not, to be honest. 
-Sit there.

865
01:02:58,121 --> 01:03:00,795
-Can I ask you something? 
-Of course.

866
01:03:02,326 --> 01:03:05,398
I find it difficult 
to understand certain things.

867
01:03:05,462 --> 01:03:07,965
-What things? 
-Well...

868
01:03:10,434 --> 01:03:12,675
I can't understand 
why this good-looking lad

869
01:03:12,736 --> 01:03:16,741
who goes to Cambridge 
without the slightest interest in politics

870
01:03:17,174 --> 01:03:20,587
and who spends his time acting 
and chasing girls,

871
01:03:21,345 --> 01:03:23,154
-suddenly ends up... 
-Married to me?

872
01:03:23,213 --> 01:03:26,126
Oh, no, not that. No, not that, at all.

873
01:03:27,684 --> 01:03:29,891
No, what I don't get

874
01:03:29,953 --> 01:03:33,332
is why, at 22, 
he's suddenly a political activist.

875
01:03:33,390 --> 01:03:36,132
-l mean, where does that come from? 
-Didn't you ask him?

876
01:03:36,193 --> 01:03:38,867
He said he joined the party because of you.

877
01:03:38,929 --> 01:03:41,739
Told me a great story about you 
turning up at his place in the rain.

878
01:03:41,799 --> 01:03:44,643
-l was gonna start the whole book with it. 
-And now you're not?

879
01:03:44,701 --> 01:03:47,739
No, I can't. it's not true.

880
01:03:49,006 --> 01:03:51,612
-Isn't it? 
-Well, you know it's not.

881
01:03:52,076 --> 01:03:54,113
He'd been a member for two years 
before he met you.

882
01:03:54,178 --> 01:03:56,021
How do you know that?

883
01:03:56,346 --> 01:03:59,816
I've got a copy 
of his original party membership card.

884
01:04:01,318 --> 01:04:03,889
Mike McAra found it in the archives.

885
01:04:03,954 --> 01:04:07,731
Typical Mike, to ruin a good story 
with too much research.

886
01:04:07,791 --> 01:04:09,793
Did he find anything else?

887
01:04:09,860 --> 01:04:12,306
Not much. Cambridge stuff mainly.

888
01:04:16,266 --> 01:04:17,768
You were more political than he was.

889
01:04:17,834 --> 01:04:21,304
I was certainly a change 
from his Cambridge girlfriends.

890
01:04:21,371 --> 01:04:24,011
All those Jocastas and Pandoras.

891
01:04:24,074 --> 01:04:27,021
And so his marriage to you 
must have been pretty vital,

892
01:04:27,077 --> 01:04:29,648
your knowledge 
and your contacts in the party.

893
01:04:29,713 --> 01:04:32,523
And I thought he married me for my body.

894
01:04:35,919 --> 01:04:39,366
Did you ever want to be 
a proper politician in your own right?

895
01:04:39,423 --> 01:04:42,632
Of course. 
Didn't you want to be a proper writer?

896
01:04:44,127 --> 01:04:45,128
Ouch.

897
01:04:47,097 --> 01:04:50,544
I'm sorry. I've hurt your feelings.

898
01:04:51,768 --> 01:04:54,612
I suppose even ghosts must have feelings.

899
01:04:55,072 --> 01:04:57,211
We are sensitive spirits.

900
01:04:59,343 --> 01:05:02,085
Talking of spirits, could you...

901
01:05:02,946 --> 01:05:04,425
Let me get you a proper drink.

902
01:05:13,557 --> 01:05:16,561
White wine, 
never really seen the point of it.

903
01:05:17,194 --> 01:05:19,470
That's the sort of thing Mike used to say.

904
01:05:19,529 --> 01:05:22,135
Ah! At last, something in common.

905
01:05:25,302 --> 01:05:28,249
Do you know the coroner reckoned 
he'd drunk nearly half a bottle?

906
01:05:28,305 --> 01:05:29,978
That's convenient.

907
01:05:30,774 --> 01:05:33,254
-What do you mean? 
-Nothing.

908
01:05:37,881 --> 01:05:41,055
-You think his death was suspicious? 
-Don't you?

909
01:05:41,118 --> 01:05:42,256
Yes.

910
01:05:44,388 --> 01:05:45,765
Yes, I do.

911
01:05:50,394 --> 01:05:52,101
Today at the beach,

912
01:05:52,529 --> 01:05:56,033
I met a man, an old timer 
who was familiar with the currents.

913
01:05:56,099 --> 01:05:57,874
And he said that there was no way

914
01:05:57,934 --> 01:06:01,279
that a body from the ferry 
could have washed ashore on that spot.

915
01:06:01,338 --> 01:06:02,373
You're kidding.

916
01:06:02,439 --> 01:06:06,649
He also said that there was a woman who 
saw flashlights on the beach that night.

917
01:06:06,710 --> 01:06:10,590
And then she fell down the stairs, 
and now she's in a coma. That's all I know.

918
01:06:10,647 --> 01:06:13,594
That's all you know? Jesus.

919
01:06:19,189 --> 01:06:21,169
-Can I borrow your phone? 
-Why?

920
01:06:21,825 --> 01:06:23,634
I need to call Adam.

921
01:06:30,000 --> 01:06:32,071
-What? 
-Nothing.

922
01:06:32,135 --> 01:06:35,548
-Aren't you gonna call him? 
-Later. I'm going out for a walk.

923
01:06:35,605 --> 01:06:38,211
But it's pitch black. it's pouring with rain.

924
01:06:38,275 --> 01:06:40,312
-It'll clear my head. 
-Well, I'll come with you.

925
01:06:40,377 --> 01:06:44,120
No. Thanks, but I need to work this one 
through on my own.

926
01:06:44,181 --> 01:06:47,162
Stay here. Have another drink. 
Don't wait up.

927
01:07:03,733 --> 01:07:04,905
(DOOR OPENING)

928
01:07:08,839 --> 01:07:10,341
Are you awake?

929
01:07:12,242 --> 01:07:14,381
-Well, I am now. 
-I'm sorry.

930
01:07:15,112 --> 01:07:18,389
It's all right. Hang on.

931
01:07:23,220 --> 01:07:25,860
-What time is it? 
-l don't know.

932
01:07:28,225 --> 01:07:29,727
I called Adam.

933
01:07:31,728 --> 01:07:34,174
-And? 
-Can I come in?

934
01:07:48,478 --> 01:07:50,719
The day before Mike died,

935
01:07:51,548 --> 01:07:53,619
he and Adam had a terrible row.

936
01:07:53,683 --> 01:07:55,788
I've never told anyone this before, 
not even the police.

937
01:07:55,852 --> 01:07:57,889
-What about? 
-l don't know.

938
01:07:58,622 --> 01:08:02,297
But it was furious. They never spoke again.

939
01:08:02,526 --> 01:08:03,937
(DISTANT THUNDERING)

940
01:08:05,829 --> 01:08:09,242
When I asked Adam about it, 
he refused to discuss it.

941
01:08:10,233 --> 01:08:14,807
After what you just said, 
I felt I should ask him again.

942
01:08:15,372 --> 01:08:17,181
And what did he say?

943
01:08:18,375 --> 01:08:20,082
He was having dinner 
with the Vice President.

944
01:08:20,143 --> 01:08:23,647
That bloody Bly woman 
wouldn't even give him the phone.

945
01:08:24,781 --> 01:08:27,591
(SOBBING) 
Oh, God. Oh, dear God.

946
01:08:29,085 --> 01:08:31,326
What's he got himself mixed up in?

947
01:08:31,388 --> 01:08:35,268
It's all right. Everything'll be all right.

948
01:08:37,394 --> 01:08:38,771
I'm scared.

949
01:08:40,030 --> 01:08:43,603
I've never been scared in my life before, 
but I am now.

950
01:08:44,067 --> 01:08:45,171
(CRYING)

951
01:08:45,469 --> 01:08:49,576
Your hair's all wet, you're drenched. 
Let me get you a towel.

952
01:09:06,223 --> 01:09:07,224
(SOFTLY) Bad idea.

953
01:09:09,192 --> 01:09:10,637
Do you mind?

954
01:09:11,461 --> 01:09:12,872
Course not.

955
01:10:12,522 --> 01:10:15,059
The modesty of the morning after?

956
01:10:15,125 --> 01:10:16,866
I'm sorry. I thought you were asleep.

957
01:10:16,960 --> 01:10:19,099
You mean you thought I'd be gone?

958
01:10:34,444 --> 01:10:38,620
You've taken out the family tree. 
He's very proud of the Langs.

959
01:10:39,149 --> 01:10:42,892
You know, if you want a family tree, 
goto a garden center.

960
01:10:44,888 --> 01:10:47,300
Why have you underlined my name 
every time?

961
01:10:47,357 --> 01:10:49,667
I was surprised 
there wasn't more about you.

962
01:10:49,726 --> 01:10:52,263
Why? I'm just the wife.

963
01:10:52,629 --> 01:10:55,473
Yeah, even so. 
You ought not to be written out of history.

964
01:10:55,532 --> 01:10:57,307
Why not? Most women are.

965
01:10:57,367 --> 01:10:59,438
Then I'll reinstate you.

966
01:11:00,103 --> 01:11:01,844
I'll put in all the occasions 
that he's forgotten.

967
01:11:01,905 --> 01:11:06,320
How kind. Like the boss's secretary 
that remembers his wife's birthday for him?

968
01:11:06,376 --> 01:11:10,722
Something like that. But then, 
like you say, I'm not a proper writer.

969
01:11:10,780 --> 01:11:13,351
-What are you planning to do? 
-Leave.

970
